{"id": 26, "ts": 1778812464.2870889, "event": "public_discussion_message", "round": 1, "agent": "agent_3", "message": "I\u2019ve taken stock of every attribute we have for the four candidates and weighed them against the core criteria for a long\u2011distance pilot: reliability, technical and cognitive competence, calmness under pressure, sound decision\u2011making, teamwork/communication, and long\u2011term professional development.\n**Candidate\u202fA**\n- Strengths: anticipates dangerous situations, sees complex connections, excellent spatial vision, very good leadership qualities.\n- Weaknesses: perceived as a show\u2011off, not open to new ideas, can be unorganized. No data on how A performs under sustained stress or long\u2011duration fatigue \u2013 a critical unknown for ultra\u2011long\u2011haul flights.\n**Candidate\u202fB**\n- Strengths: very conscientious, handles stress well, good at assessing weather, excellent computer skills.\n- Weaknesses: relatively weak memory for numbers, makes nasty remarks and can be grumpy/uncooperative, which could erode crew cohesion.\n**Candidate\u202fC**\n- Strengths: makes correct decisions quickly, stays calm in a crisis, understands complicated technology, excellent attention skills, puts concern for others above everything.\n- Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas, regarded as egocentric, not very willing to pursue further education \u2013 all detrimental to teamwork and future development.\n**Candidate\u202fD**\n- Strengths: responds adequately to unexpected events, concentrates very well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously.\n- Weaknesses: regarded as a know\u2011it\u2011all/arrogant, has a hot temper, relatively weak leadership skills. We have no information on D\u2019s ability to handle prolonged stress or fatigue, nor on his crew\u2011interaction style beyond the arrogance/temper issues.\nOverall, Candidate\u202fA offers the strongest combination of technical competence, anticipatory